**Abstract:**
A variant of "On MacIntyre, Rationality, and Dramatic Space" examining rationality and the subject-world relationship. Contains the same core arguments as 96-DEC-3 about the Platonic contemplative tradition, Husserl's epoché, and the concept of dramatic space as the space populated by beings affected by events. Develops the distinction between description and narration, arguing novels require dramatic space because things cannot be narrative characters.

**AI Recommendation:** Variant of 96-DEC-3 essay; compare for textual differences.

